28:15.093 --> 28:18.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUSAN HELPER: I think that one
of the things
now, we have greater experience.

28:18.730 --> 28:21.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We can see what -- what's
happened as a result
of some of the trade agreements.

28:21.433 --> 28:28.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's some very excellent work
that suggests
that workers who are displaced
by trade or

28:28.740 --> 28:32.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other reasons, but particularly
by trade,
don't easily find new jobs.

28:32.411 --> 28:37.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And particularly in the case of
a lost manufacturing
job, the new job that somebody
gets doesn't

28:37.382 --> 28:39.184 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
equal their previous wage.

28:39.217 --> 28:43.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But many economists
argue, robots,
not trade deals, are the real
job-robbers.

28:43.722 --> 28:50.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I asked Sherrod Brown, isn't
it technology
that's actually replacing jobs,
as opposed

28:50.128 --> 28:51.096 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to unfair trade?

28:51.129 --> 28:52.097 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

28:52.130 --> 28:53.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHERROD BROWN: Well, it's all of
the above.

28:53.131 --> 28:54.132 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's unfair trade practices.

28:54.166 --> 28:55.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's technology.

28:55.534 --> 28:58.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
About five miles from my home is
a company
called ArcelorMittal.

28:58.670 --> 29:06.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That plant was the first plant
in world history
where close to one person hour
of labor produces

29:06.778 --> 29:08.046 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
one ton of steel.

29:08.080 --> 29:10.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's technology, that's
efficiency.

29:10.315 --> 29:12.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's put some steelworkers out
of work because
they're so efficient.

29:12.651 --> 29:13.619 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Right.

29:13.652 --> 29:15.420 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

29:15.454 --> 29:18.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERROD BROWN: But unfair trade
practices
has also -- have also put a lot
of those workers

29:18.423 --> 29:20.225 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out of work.

29:20.258 --> 29:23.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Moreover, Susan
Helper's research
suggests that technology can
actually add

29:23.795 --> 29:26.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
jobs at ArcelorMittal or
anywhere else.

29:27.032 --> 29:30.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SUSAN HELPER: When your
productivity goes
up, your price falls, so more
people are going

29:30.936 --> 29:33.538 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to want to buy things made out
of steel.

29:33.572 --> 29:38.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We looked at manufacturing
industries over
the last couple of decades, and
found that

29:38.710 --> 29:43.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
those industries that had the
greatest productivity
growth actually had the most job
gains.

29:43.982 --> 29:44.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: But why?

29:44.983 --> 29:46.818 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SUSAN HELPER: Because they found
new markets.

29:46.852 --> 29:51.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They were able to expand into
new markets
and find new uses for the
technology that

29:51.123 --> 29:52.924 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they had innovated.

29:52.958 --> 29:56.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Even so, Sherrod
Brown believes
candidate Clinton's tougher
stance on trade

29:56.695 --> 29:57.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is a welcome one.

29:57.696 --> 29:59.531 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

29:59.564 --> 30:01.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERROD BROWN: I'm glad we are
most efficient
steel plant in the world less
than 10 miles

30:01.600 --> 30:05.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from here, but we have got a lot
of work to
do to make sure trade
enforcement is done

30:05.837 --> 30:07.906 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the way Secretary Clinton wants
it done.

30:07.939 --> 30:10.542 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that -- that will ultimately
provide jobs.

30:10.575 --> 30:11.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It will save jobs.

30:11.576 --> 30:13.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It will help manufacturing
rebirth.

30:13.378 --> 30:21.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: This is economics
correspondent
Paul Solman in and around
Cleveland, Ohio.

30:21.286 --> 30:33.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In Caracas,
today, hundreds
of thousands of Venezuelans
turned out to

30:33.198 --> 30:38.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
protest against President
Nicolas Maduro's
government and called for an end
to his rule.

30:38.437 --> 30:43.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The country has been plagued by
a deepening
economic crisis, corruption,
crime, all of

30:43.508 --> 30:46.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which have contributed to a
worsening food
shortage.

30:46.578 --> 30:50.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nathan Halverson of Reveal from
the Center
for Investigative Reporting
recently visited

30:50.849 --> 30:52.684 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Caracas,.

30:52.718 --> 30:57.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: Well before
sunrise, hungry
Venezuelans are waiting outside
grocery stores

30:57.089 --> 30:59.257 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
praying for food trucks to
arrive.

30:59.291 --> 31:02.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By mid-morning, with streets
crowded with
anxious faces, there is little
hope.

31:02.561 --> 31:05.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
There is only
butter and oil.

31:05.964 --> 31:07.599 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We need them to send us more
food.

31:07.632 --> 31:09.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION (through translator):
When did you
get here?

31:09.034 --> 31:10.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): At
4:00 a.m.

31:10.302 --> 31:14.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): I got
here at 8:00
p.m. last night.

31:14.039 --> 31:18.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As Venezuelans watch their
country crumble
and their desperation and hunger
spill into

31:18.643 --> 31:24.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the streets, their anger with
President Nicolas
Maduro and his party has become
explosive.

31:24.249 --> 31:27.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): This
is what's
happening in Venezuela.

31:27.319 --> 31:28.286 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We're starving.

31:28.320 --> 31:31.790 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're struggling, thanks to this
government.

31:31.823 --> 31:34.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's the Maduro diet.

31:34.726 --> 31:38.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: Police now
guard grocery
stores across the country,
holding back the

31:38.897 --> 31:40.165 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hungry and volatile mobs.

31:40.198 --> 31:42.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): Why
are you taking
me out of line?

31:42.300 --> 31:43.268 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was here early.

31:43.301 --> 31:45.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I also need food.

31:45.237 --> 31:48.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: Some 90
percent of Venezuelans
now report that food has become
too expensive

31:48.707 --> 31:50.242 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to buy.

31:50.275 --> 31:54.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hungry mobs are increasingly
rioting and looting
bakeries and food trucks.

31:54.312 --> 31:59.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has forced everyday people
to try and
calm desperate crowds, like this
grocery store

31:59.584 --> 32:00.752 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
manager.

32:00.786 --> 32:02.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): We
don't produce
the food.

32:02.254 --> 32:03.588 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Everyone is waiting for
something to arrive.

32:03.622 --> 32:06.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If it doesn't arrive, we can't
create food
from nothing.

32:06.591 --> 32:10.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: People are
losing hope that
the government-controlled system
will supply

32:10.529 --> 32:11.797 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
key items.

32:11.830 --> 32:14.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they blame the socialist
government for
the scarcity.

32:14.266 --> 32:17.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): It's
one article
of food per person, and then you
have to wait

32:17.736 --> 32:20.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
eight days, because if you try
to buy more,
they will stop you.

32:20.972 --> 32:26.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: The result is
hunger, and
a country increasingly turning
against President

32:26.378 --> 32:28.213 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Nicolas Maduro.

32:28.246 --> 32:33.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAULA GIRAUD, Journalist
(through translator):
My friends have lost weight, 15,
20, 25 pounds

32:33.151 --> 32:34.920 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
even.

32:34.953 --> 32:37.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: Paula Giraud
is a journalist
who writes a food blog about the
country's

32:37.823 --> 32:39.691 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rapidly worsening situation.

32:39.724 --> 32:42.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAULA GIRAUD (through
translator): I'm afraid
there will be, although the
government doesn't

32:42.994 --> 32:47.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
want to see it, and I don't want
to either,
a social explosion of immense
proportions.

32:48.033 --> 32:53.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: Usually, her
only meal for
an entire day is one egg.

32:53.705 --> 32:57.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAULA GIRAUD: Only one egg, no
more.

32:57.709 --> 33:02.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: And she has to
share it
with her dog.

33:02.714 --> 33:05.083 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The impacts are widespread.

33:05.116 --> 33:07.385 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Schoolchildren are fainting from
hunger.

33:07.419 --> 33:10.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHILD (through translator): In
my house, there
is no food.

33:10.989 --> 33:14.025 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NATHAN HALVERSON: School
principal Malkis
Mochado (ph) says some students
don't even

33:14.059 --> 33:16.127 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have the energy to attend.

33:16.161 --> 33:19.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: When you were absent from
school, why
didn't you come?

33:19.965 --> 33:21.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHILD (through translator):
Because I had
nothing to eat.

33:21.967 --> 33:25.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: The school now
provides
what is sometimes the only meal
these children

33:25.904 --> 33:26.972 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
eat.

33:27.005 --> 33:28.940 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Food has become political.

33:28.974 --> 33:33.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In August, the opposition party
started this
school lunch program, winning
the gratitude

33:33.478 --> 33:35.413 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of a hungry community.

33:35.447 --> 33:39.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, for others, food still
remains hard to
find.

33:39.150 --> 33:42.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): I have
a job, but
what's the point?

33:42.220 --> 33:43.421 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
My salary is worth nothing.

33:43.455 --> 33:47.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, you can't even get
rice or corn
flour.

33:47.259 --> 33:50.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For everything, you have to wait
in line.

33:50.495 --> 33:54.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: After work,
men gather on
street corners to scavenge for
food, rather

33:54.799 --> 33:57.969 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
than skip work to wait in line
all day.

33:58.003 --> 34:02.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These workers once shopped at
government-subsidized
grocery stores like this one
once, but now

34:02.374 --> 34:06.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the shelves here are completely
empty.

34:06.144 --> 34:11.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But for some well-connected
people, there
are still reliable sources of
food.

34:11.049 --> 34:14.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Government employees receive
privileged access
at this warehouse.

34:14.719 --> 34:18.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are government workers and
their friends
carting off items that most
Venezuelans can

34:18.723 --> 34:24.896 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
no longer afford or even find on
the shelves.

34:24.930 --> 34:29.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Paula Giraud said the government
is using
the food to control people, to
buy their support,

34:29.668 --> 34:31.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and was outraged by what we
filmed.

34:31.503 --> 34:35.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAULA GIRAUD (through
translator): Every week
in the country, the hunger
increases.

34:35.173 --> 34:38.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The shortages increase and the
corruption
increases.

34:38.076 --> 34:40.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
That's what millions and
millions of Venezuelans
are enduring.

34:40.812 --> 34:46.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHAN HALVERSON: For the
country, the societal
explosion that many fear seems
to be inching

34:46.785 --> 34:47.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
closer every day.

34:48.019 --> 34:58.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Nathan Halverson
in Caracas.

34:58.496 --> 35:09.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In recent
years, a number
of prestigious colleges and
universities have

35:09.441 --> 35:13.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had to acknowledge their past
ties and history
to slavery in the U.S.

35:14.012 --> 35:19.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, Georgetown University
became the latest
to say it will apologize for its
past and

35:19.217 --> 35:21.119 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
take new steps.

35:21.152 --> 35:26.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More than 200 years ago, the
original Georgetown
College operated plantations in
Maryland that

35:26.324 --> 35:28.159 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
worked with slave labor.

35:28.193 --> 35:34.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then, in 1838, facing deep debt,
a pair of
priests who each served as
president of Georgetown

35:34.933 --> 35:38.937 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sold 272 people to help pay the
bills.

35:38.970 --> 35:42.474 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The slaves were sent to
plantations in Louisiana.

35:42.507 --> 35:46.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help atone for its past, the
university
announced it would give a
special preference

35:46.711 --> 35:51.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in admissions to applicants who
are descendants
of Georgetown's slaves.

35:51.683 --> 35:57.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's also renaming a building in
honor of
one of the slaves, erecting a
public memorial,

35:57.489 --> 36:01.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and creating an institute to
study slavery
and its legacy.

36:01.326 --> 36:04.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
University president John
DeGioia spoke at
a news conference today.

36:04.696 --> 36:09.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN DEGIOIA, President,
Georgetown University:
So many were surprised, even
shocked, by the

36:09.401 --> 36:15.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
revelation of Jesuit
slaveholding and the
benefit we received from the
1830 sale.

36:15.240 --> 36:25.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As a community and as
individuals, we cannot
do our best work if we refuse to
take ownership

36:25.050 --> 36:28.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of such a critical part of our
history.

36:28.386 --> 36:30.288 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We must acknowledge it.

36:30.321 --> 36:33.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For a closer
look at this,
I'm joined from New York by
Craig Steven Wilder.

36:33.691 --> 36:38.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's a professor of American
history at Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, and
author of "Ebony

36:38.496 --> 36:42.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Ivy: Race, Slavery, and the
Troubled History
of America's Universities."

36:42.400 --> 36:44.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mr. Wilder, put this in context
for us.

36:44.302 --> 36:48.907 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How crucial was this transaction
of people
to keep Georgetown alive?

36:48.940 --> 36:52.143 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER,
Massachusetts Institute
of Technology: You know, in
1838, Georgetown

36:52.177 --> 36:57.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
sold -- the president of
Georgetown helped
negotiate the sale of about 272
people to

36:57.315 --> 36:59.117 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Louisiana.

36:59.150 --> 37:04.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And from what we understand,
about 15 to 20
percent of the money, the
proceeds, actually

37:04.122 --> 37:06.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
was used to pay down
Georgetown's debts.

37:06.524 --> 37:11.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think it's actually
quite crucial
to the continued survival of the
university.

37:11.463 --> 37:16.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is about the time that the
university
imposed tuition for the first
time.

37:16.334 --> 37:19.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so it was helping to meet a
number of
financial needs.

37:19.137 --> 37:23.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about
your thoughts
on the university's actions
today?

37:23.241 --> 37:28.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: I thought
that the report
was thorough and quite
thoughtful, but the

37:28.546 --> 37:32.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
real meaning of the report --
I'm cautiously
optimistic -- I think the real
meaning of

37:32.217 --> 37:38.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the report will get revealed
over the next
several years and decades, as we
see Georgetown

37:38.189 --> 37:39.958 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
implement these promises.

37:39.991 --> 37:46.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it will depend upon how
fully those get
institutionalized on the campus,
and so that

37:46.064 --> 37:47.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we can actually see them really
get achieved.

37:47.966 --> 37:53.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, how --
today, there
was a clause in there about
admissions preference.

37:53.104 --> 37:54.939 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Explain that.

37:54.973 --> 37:58.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: Well, I
think what they're
doing is, they're looking at the
descendants

37:58.209 --> 38:05.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the 272 people who were sold
in 1838, and
seeking to bring them to campus
and to give

38:05.884 --> 38:11.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them preferential admission to
Georgetown,
actually like a lot of
populations of students

38:11.055 --> 38:12.824 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
do.

38:12.857 --> 38:17.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For instance, the children of
alumni often
get preferential treatment in
admissions.

38:17.328 --> 38:21.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so this would extend that to
the children
of the people sold -- or the
descendants of

38:21.499 --> 38:23.201 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the people sold in 1838.

38:23.234 --> 38:26.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How does this
compare to
what other schools are doing
these days?

38:26.571 --> 38:34.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: That step
is actually
-- takes the response to slavery
further than

38:34.512 --> 38:37.715 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
any other institution has gone.

38:37.749 --> 38:44.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other actions inside the
report actually
are fairly similar to what other
institutions

38:44.622 --> 38:49.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have done, for instance, the
renaming of two
of the buildings on the
Georgetown campus,

38:49.294 --> 38:54.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the decision to create a
memorial to slavery
on the campus, and the decision
to establish

38:54.899 --> 38:56.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an institute for the study of
slavery.

38:56.768 --> 39:01.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of the
dangers is that
this almost creates a checklist
for a university

39:01.472 --> 39:02.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that says, OK, fine, I have got
a memorial,
check.

39:02.907 --> 39:04.676 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm going to do this, check.

39:04.709 --> 39:09.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that long-lasting change
you're talking
about, that could take years to
get through

39:09.681 --> 39:12.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the student body and the entire
campus.

39:12.317 --> 39:14.953 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: And I think
that's the
key to this.

39:14.986 --> 39:21.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A report does not bring closure
to the story
of Georgetown's relationship to
slavery.

39:21.559 --> 39:27.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What will ultimately begin to, I
hope, heal
and repair the relationship
between Georgetown,

39:27.832 --> 39:33.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Catholic Church and the
descendants of
the people sold in 1838 will be,
in fact,

39:33.104 --> 39:36.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Georgetown fulfilling these
commitments in
a really quite holistic way.

39:36.374 --> 39:40.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And does this
blaze the
trail for other universities,
considering

39:40.545 --> 39:42.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that there are already some that
are tackling
this?

39:42.714 --> 39:44.482 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: I think it
does.

39:44.515 --> 39:49.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that what you will see
is, in fact,
a continued conversation about
the legacies

39:49.420 --> 39:54.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of slavery on our campuses, and
also the thing
that's actually has kept much of
this discussion

39:54.559 --> 39:59.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
alive for the past several
years, student
activism on campus, which has,
in fact, been

39:59.297 --> 40:02.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the instrument for keeping this
conversation
alive.

40:02.400 --> 40:06.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, has
Georgetown taken
steps to try to track down the
descendants?

40:06.638 --> 40:11.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because, when you think about
it, 272 people
from the 1800s, that actually
could be thousands

40:11.242 --> 40:13.177 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of people by now.

40:13.211 --> 40:15.013 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: Right.

40:15.046 --> 40:19.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And one of the sort of
remarkable things about
the Georgetown situation is that
the records

40:19.150 --> 40:24.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the Jesuits kept of that
sale are actually
really quite complete.

40:24.756 --> 40:30.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, with the assistance --
actually, really,
in many ways, the alumni sort of
pushed this

40:30.561 --> 40:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
conversation, members of the
alumni community
of Georgetown, and actually
helped to both

40:35.767 --> 40:40.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fund and encourage the process
of reaching
out and going out to Louisiana
and helping

40:40.772 --> 40:47.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to track the genealogies of the
families who
are related to those 272 slaves.

40:47.045 --> 40:50.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And we're
talking a lot
about Georgetown today and a few
other schools,

40:50.481 --> 40:54.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but, really, when you look up
and down the
Eastern Seaboard for hundreds of
years, all

40:54.619 --> 40:59.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the early, early colleges
likely had some
of this in their past.

40:59.090 --> 41:03.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: Yes, every
college established
before the American Revolution
-- there are

41:03.094 --> 41:07.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nine colleges established before
the revolution
in the British colonies.

41:07.198 --> 41:11.169 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They're all, in fact,
established by slave
traders and slave owners.

41:11.202 --> 41:16.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After the American Revolution,
we established
17 colleges, one every year
until 1800.

41:16.240 --> 41:20.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those colleges have close ties
to slavery
because they're founded with the
recovery

41:20.678 --> 41:22.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the slave economy after the
war.

41:22.847 --> 41:27.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in the decades before the
Civil War, it's
the rise of the cotton economy
that drives

41:27.618 --> 41:29.987 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the expansion of American higher
education.

41:30.021 --> 41:34.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the story of American
education, higher
education in particular, is the
story of American

41:34.592 --> 41:35.927 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
slavery.

41:35.960 --> 41:37.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Craig Steven
Wilder, thanks so much.

41:37.362 --> 41:39.063 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CRAIG STEVEN WILDER: Thank you.

41:39.097 --> 41:41.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Online, the
discussion of
race continues.

41:41.733 --> 41:46.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Milwaukee was rocked by riots
last month after
a young man was killed by
police.

41:46.637 --> 41:50.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We talked to community leaders
and city officials
about the city's history of
segregation and

41:50.742 --> 41:56.381 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what hope there is for future
generations.

41:56.414 --> 42:08.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Now to another of
our Brief But
Spectacular interviews.

42:08.192 --> 42:13.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from Daniel
Handler, a name
you may only recognize if we
identify him

42:13.164 --> 42:15.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
by his alias, Lemony Snicket.

42:15.600 --> 42:22.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL HANDLER, Author: When I
was researching
my first novel, "The Basic
Eight," I was calling

42:22.607 --> 42:27.612 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
up right-wing religious
organization and political
groups in order to make fun of
them.

42:27.645 --> 42:29.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I thought to myself, I
better not tell
her my real name.

42:29.781 --> 42:32.350 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I will be on their mailing list
forever.

42:32.383 --> 42:33.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, she said, "What is your
name?"

42:33.785 --> 42:35.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, I said, "Lemony Snicket."

42:35.753 --> 42:38.089 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And then there was a pause.

42:38.122 --> 42:41.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I thought, out of all the
things you could
have said, that was the worst
one.

42:41.626 --> 42:43.428 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No one was going to believe
that.

42:43.461 --> 42:54.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then the woman from the
right-wing organization
said, "Is that spelled how it
sounds?"

42:54.305 --> 42:57.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I was 5 years old, someone
asked me what
I wanted to be when I grew up,
and I said

42:57.842 --> 43:01.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that I wanted to be an old man
who lived on
the top of a mountain giving
advice.

43:01.045 --> 43:02.146 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't remember it.

43:02.180 --> 43:04.315 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
All I remember is wanting to be
a writer.

43:04.348 --> 43:05.783 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I would read on the bus.

43:05.817 --> 43:08.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I would miss the bus because I
was reading.

43:08.119 --> 43:12.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first book that I bought
with my own money
was "The Blue Aspic" by Edward
Gorey.

43:12.790 --> 43:16.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, when the first two
volumes of "A
Series of Unfortunate Events"
were ready to

43:16.794 --> 43:20.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be published, I sent them to
Edward Gorey
with a note saying how much I
admired his

43:20.631 --> 43:25.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
work and how much I hoped that
he would forgive
what I had stolen from him.

43:25.336 --> 43:27.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Shortly after I sent it, he
died.

43:27.672 --> 43:29.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I like to think that I
killed him.

43:29.941 --> 43:34.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So much of children's literature
is about
enforced fun or enforced
morality.

43:34.045 --> 43:38.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Surely, you will be rewarded if
you behave
this way, or aren't you having a
wonderful

43:38.783 --> 43:40.685 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
time reading about this?

43:40.718 --> 43:41.853 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And you never are.

43:41.886 --> 43:43.721 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it never goes that way.

43:43.754 --> 43:47.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, part of "A Series of
Unfortunate Events"
was an acknowledgment of the
bewildering state

43:47.058 --> 43:48.826 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of affair that is childhood.

43:48.860 --> 43:52.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION: Do you have a notebook
on you right
now?

43:52.196 --> 43:53.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL HANDLER: I do.

43:53.197 --> 43:55.032 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I do have a notebook on me right
now.

43:55.066 --> 43:58.135 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is my notebook.

43:58.169 --> 44:02.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think of things or I read
them, and then
I write them down in the
notebook.

44:02.340 --> 44:07.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I type it onto a document on my
computer,
tape them or paste on to index
cards.

44:07.745 --> 44:10.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I move all the index cards
around.

44:10.114 --> 44:12.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I write it on a legal pad
longhand.

44:12.250 --> 44:15.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I type up the legal pad onto
another document.

44:15.152 --> 44:17.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It makes me look largely like a
serial killer.

44:17.655 --> 44:21.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I work in public, people
clutch their
children tighter because they're
walking by

44:21.225 --> 44:26.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a man sipping an espresso moving
pasted index
cards around and writing on a
legal pad.

44:26.964 --> 44:28.432 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That man's not to be trusted.

44:28.466 --> 44:31.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION: You say, it's OK, I'm
writing a
children's book.

44:31.102 --> 44:32.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL HANDLER: Yes.

44:32.103 --> 44:33.070 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I say, don't worry.

44:33.104 --> 44:34.572 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm in narrative prose.

44:34.605 --> 44:39.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A writer's relationship with
rejection is
like that of a fish to water.

44:39.577 --> 44:40.978 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's all that's there.

44:41.012 --> 44:47.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think you should feel it and
feel utter
despair and then move on.

44:47.718 --> 44:52.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was going to say something
about technology's
influence on reading, but then I
got a text,

44:52.123 --> 44:53.524 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and I just have to answer it.

44:53.558 --> 44:55.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can I just -- I will be right
back.

44:55.293 --> 44:58.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a triumph of finding
specific things
and an utter failure of finding
something

44:58.062 --> 44:59.730 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that you didn't know you were
looking for.

44:59.764 --> 45:02.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I exist in a state of
bewilderment almost
all of the time.

45:02.934 --> 45:08.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Am I grasping at the hem of some
large idea
that is worth investigating?

45:08.372 --> 45:14.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I mull this over all day
long, whether
this thing that I'm pulling is a
thread that

45:14.211 --> 45:18.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
will lead me through the
labyrinth or just
a thread that will dismantle the
sweater.

45:18.983 --> 45:21.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My name is Daniel Handler, AKA
Lemony Snicket.

45:21.519 --> 45:26.390 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And this is my Brief But
Spectacular take
on a bewildering world.

45:26.424 --> 45:29.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
